AN ACT relating to medical debt; prohibiting collection agencies
and certain entities that provide health care from reporting
medical debt to a consumer reporting agency in certain
circumstances; prohibiting certain actions by certain
entities that provide health care and collection agencies to
collect a medical debt; providing requirements for
engaging in extraordinary collection actions to collect a
medical debt; authorizing the Commissioner of Financial
Institutions to institute legal proceedings against violators;
and providing other matters properly relating thereto.
Legislative Counsel’s Digest:
1 Existing law provides requirements governing the collection of medical debt by
2 a collection agency, including a requirement to provide certain notice to a medical
3 debtor before taking action to collect and prohibiting certain actions to collect a
4 medical debt. (NRS 649.366, 649.368) Section 13 of this bill prohibits a health care
5 entity, which includes a medical facility, provider of health care or provider of
6 emergency medical services, or a collection agency from reporting a medical debt
7 to a consumer reporting agency unless the health care entity or collection agency
8 issued an offer to the consumer to enter into a payment plan to satisfy the medical
9 debt. Section 13: (1) establishes a procedure for the issuance of such an offer; (2)
10 prohibits a health care entity or collection agency from reporting medical debt to a
11 consumer reporting agency if the consumer enters into a payment plan and
12 complies with the terms and conditions of the plan; (3) provides that any portion of
13 the medical debt that is reported to a consumer reporting agency in violation of
14 section 13 shall be void; and (4) requires the Commissioner of Financial
15 Institutions to adopt regulations to carry out the provisions of section 13. Sections
16 14 and 19 of this bill prohibit a health care entity or collection agency from
17 engaging in certain actions, or threatening to engage in certain actions, to collect a
18 medical debt, including: (1) causing the arrest of a consumer; (2) obtaining a lien or
-
